'''Bathvillite''' is a naturally occurring [[organic substance]]. It is an amorphous, opaque, and very friable material of fawn-brown color, filling cavities in the [[torbanite]] or [[Boghead coal]] of [[Bathville]], [[Lothian]], [[Scotland]]. It has a specific gravity of 1.01, and is insoluble in [[benzene]].<ref>{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Bathvillite |volume=3 |page=521}}</ref> It may resemble wood in its final stage of decay.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=aG4NAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA742&lpg=PA742&dq=Bathvillite&source=bl&ots=aLwCPYZx25&sig=owLAXQICrYZMZ-XQfNrCLfKpGgU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiyk6zz0vTSAhUW24MKHWJHAz4Q6AEIPDAI#v=onepage&q=Bathvillite&f=false|title=A System of Mineralogy: Descriptive Mineralogy, Comprising the Most Recent Discoveries|last=Dana|first=James Dwight|last2=Brush|first2=George Jarvis|year=1884|publisher=J. Wiley & sons|language=en}}</ref>

