{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Carlo Beenakker | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = Carlo_Beenakker.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Carlo Beenakker at Leiden University in April 2007 | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|6|9|mf=yes}} | birth_place = [[Leiden]] | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = [[Dutch people|Dutch]] | nationality = | fields = [[Theoretical physics]] | workplaces = | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[Leiden University]] | thesis_title = On transport properties of concentrated suspensions | thesis_url = <!--(or | thesis1_url = and | thesis2_url = )--> | thesis_year = 1984 | doctoral_advisor = [[Peter Mazur]] | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = [[Spinoza Prize]] {{small|(1999)}} | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = {{URL|https://www.lorentz.leidenuniv.nl/beenakker/}} | footnotes = }}
'''Carlo Willem Joannes Beenakker''' (born June 9, 1960) is a professor at [[Leiden University]] and leader of the university's [[mesoscopic]] [[physics]] group, established in 1992.
==Early life and education== Born in [[Leiden]] as the son of physicists {{Interlanguage link multi|Jan Beenakker|nl}} and Elena Manaresi,<ref>http://www.nrcreader.nl/artikel/6319/ik-wil-zo-dicht-mogelijk-bij-onsterfelijkheid-komen</ref> Beenakker graduated from Leiden University in 1982 and obtained his doctorate two years later.
==Career== After the awarding of his doctorate, he then spent one year working in the [[United States of America]] as a fellow of the Niels Stensen Foundation before returning to the Netherlands as a member of the scientific staff of the [[Philips]] Research Laboratories in [[Eindhoven]]. He was made External Professor of [[theoretical physics|Theoretical Physics]] at Leiden in 1991.
His work in mesoscopic physics addresses fundamental physical problems that occur when a [[macroscopic]] object is miniaturized.
In 1993, he shared the Royal/Shell prize for "the discovery and explanation of quantum effects in the [[electrical conduction]] in mesoscopic systems". He was elected a member of the Royal Holland Society of Sciences and Humanities in 2001, and the [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.knaw.nl/en/members/members/5076 |title=Carlo Beenakker |publisher=Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences |date= |accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> He was awarded one of the Netherlands' most prestigious science awards, the [[Spinozapremie]], in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.nwo.nl/en/research-and-results/programmes/spinoza+prize/spinoza+laureates/overview+by+year/1999 |title=NWO Spinoza Prize 1999 |publisher=Netherlands Organisation for Scientific Research |date=11 September 2014 |accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref> In 2006 he was honored with the [[AkzoNobel]] Science Award "for his pioneering work in the field of [[nanoscience]]".{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}
In a 1997 study by the Institute for Scientific Information, Beenakker rated in the top 300 most cited physicists of the previous 16 years.{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}
In 2008, Beenakker attended the 24th [[Solvay Conference]] on Physics.<ref>[http://www.lorentz.leidenuniv.nl/history/Solvay/solvay.html Lorentz & the Solvay conferences], Instituut-Lorentz, Leiden University</ref>
