{{Infobox scientist | name = Gustav Flor | image = Gustav Flor.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Gustav Flor | birth_date = 13 August 1829 | birth_place = [[Salacgrīva Municipality|Vecsalaca]], [[Governorate of Livonia]] (present-day [[Latvia]]) | death_date = 13 May 1883 | death_place = [[Tartu]], [[Governorate of Livonia]] (present-day [[Estonia]]) | nationality = [[Baltic Germans|Baltic German]] | fields = [[Zoology]] | workplaces = [[University of Tartu]] }} '''Gustav August Adam Flor''' (13 August 1829, [[Salacgrīva Municipality|Vecsalaca]] ({{lang-de|Alt-Salis}}),<ref>[[List of German exonyms for places in Latvia#A]]</ref> present-day [[Latvia]] &ndash; 13 May 1883 [[Tartu]] ({{lang-de|Dorpat}}), present-day [[Estonia]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Biografien der Entomologen der Welt : Datenbank. Version 4.15|url=http://sdei.de/biographies/|publisher=Senckenberg Deutsches Entomologisches Institut|accessdate=31 December 2011|author=Groll, E.K. (ed.)|language=German|year=2010}}</ref> was a [[Baltic Germans|Baltic German]] [[zoologist]] from [[Governorate of Livonia|Livonia]].
==Life and career== Flor studied medicine and natural science at the [[University of Dorpat]], later becoming a professor of zoology. In 1860, he became director of the zoological cabinet, which he remained until his death in 1883 (the zoological cabinet was the predecessor of the Zoology Museum at the University of Tartu, where his 11,815-specimen entomological collection still resides).<ref>{{cite web|title=Museum of Zoology: History|url=http://www.ut.ee/BGZM/history/history.html|publisher=University of Tartu Natural History Museum|accessdate=31 December 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219232716/http://www.ut.ee/BGZM/history/history.html|archivedate=19 February 2012|df=}}</ref>
He is best known for his studies of [[Hemiptera]], especially the two-volume work ''Die Rhynchoten Livlands in systematischer Folge beschrieben'' ("''The Hemiptera of [[Governorate of Livonia|Livonia]], Described In Systematic Order''").<ref>{{cite journal|title=Obituary|journal=Entomologist's Monthly Magazine|year=1883–1884|volume=20|url=https://archive.org/stream/entomologistsmo26compgoog#page/n102/mode/1up|accessdate=31 December 2011|page=72|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ryder|first=David A.|title=Biographical & Type Information- F|url=http://www.ndsu.nodak.edu/ndsu/rider/Pentatomoidea/Biographical/biographical_F.htm|work=Pentatomidea Home Page|publisher=North Dakota State University, Fargo|accessdate=31 December 2011|year=2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207142230/http://www.ndsu.nodak.edu/ndsu/rider/Pentatomoidea/Biographical/biographical_F.htm|archivedate=7 February 2012|df=}}</ref>
