{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}
'''James Ayscough''' (died 1759) was an English [[optician]] and designer and maker of [[scientific instruments]]. He was apprenticed to an optician named [[James Mann (optician)|James Mann]] from 1743 to 1747. James Ayscough became known for his [[microscope]]s. His shop was in [[London]] between 1740 and 1759. Around the year 1752, James Ayscough introduced [[spectacles]] with double-hinged side pieces.<ref>{{cite journal | last =Washizu | first =Hiroko  | title =The Optics of Green Spectacles | journal =The Edgar Allan Poe Review | volume =12 | issue =2 | page =49 | publisher = Penn State University Press | date =2011 | jstor =41506455 }}</ref> Although he made clear [[Lens (optics)|lenses]], he recommended lenses tinted blue or green to treat some vision problems.  These [[spectacles]] with tinted lenses are believed to be the precursors to [[sunglasses]].

