'''Pauline Dy Phon''' (ប៉ូលីន ឌី ផុន) (1933-21 May 2010) was a Cambodian botanist who specialized in the flora of South East Asia.

Coming to study in France, she obtained her license in 1959 at the Faculty of Sciences in Paris. She became teacher and researcher at the [[University of Phnom Penh]], though in 1975 she was forced to stop work because the [[Khmer Rouge]] came to power.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aefek.free.fr/travaux/iso_album/dy_phon_edito.pdf|title=Editorial|publisher=Aefek.free.fr|format=PDF|language=French|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref> In 1980, she managed to flee to France and work in the Botanical Laboratory of the National Museum of Natural History. In the same institution she contributed significantly to identifying and classifying plants of Cambodia and Indochina, which remain relatively unknown.<ref>{{cite book|title=Culture khmère|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AA0rAAAAMAAJ|year=1981|publisher=CEDORECK|language=French|page=189}}</ref> In 1980 she was awarded the [[Prix de Coincy]] by the [[Académie des Sciences]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Comptes rendus des séances de l'Académie des sciences: Vie académique|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BA8gAQAAMAAJ|year=1980|publisher=Gauthier-Villars|page=124}}</ref> She published a 915-page directory of the ''Dictionary of plants used in Cambodia'' in 2000.<ref name="Phon2000">{{cite book|last=Phon|first=Pauline Dy|title=Dictionary of plants used in Cambodia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=InD2RAAACAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Dy Phon Pauline}}</ref>

